<TITLE> CA asks imams to preach against militancy, corruption </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 5 (bdnews24.com) - Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed Monday called on the imams of mosques to be good citizens and to be vigilant of militancy, crime and corruption. He said since imams were held in high esteem and sought out for ethical advice they had a special responsibility in building an enlightened society. The chief adviser made the call at the national conference of imams at Osmany Memorial Auditorium. He urged imams to preach against social evils, serious crimes and corruption at Friday sermons and at other religious congregations. Fakhruddin asked imams to translate the Arabic portion of the Khutba to Bangla. He said Bangladesh's society would not return to the corrupt state that it was in before Jan 11. He urged religious leaders to teach moral duties like living with honesty, sincerity and integrity. The chief adviser also mentioned that the Imam-Muezzin Trust Fund had been raised to Tk 9 crore from Tk 4 crore, and that imams were eligible to take loans from the Trust. Religious affairs adviser ASM Motiur Rahman presided over the meeting. Religious affairs secretary Ataur Rahman, Islamic Foundation director general Fazlur Rahman, UNFPA acting director Prontai Suchitta, and Chittagong Baitul Ohhab Jame Masjid Khatib Munirul Islam also spoke. bdnews24.c
